<br>
The Geneva Convention is supposed to guide militaries through wartime or conflict, although not all militaries abide, or even recognize it. Unnecessary cruelty, exchange of officers, what information you can give the enemy, denying medical attention to prisoners, and so on, are covered. <br>
<br>
If you are serving during a time of war/conflict and happen to be multilingual you may be asked to perform a soft interview. You speak with the prisoner, try to get answers, convince him it's in his best interest to talk. If he doesn't budge and depending on how badly they need information you will be asked to leave, and (more or less) civilians take over. The GC doesn't apply to organizations like the CIA. I doubt they tried talking again. Derived knowledge from a Gulf War vet. <br>
<br>
When I mentioned torture I was speaking in a general sense, not pointing the prisoners in Cuba out. IMO, and this is strictly my opinion, if CIA agents are on the premises torture in any degree is a possibility. KGB, what have you; they don't fly halfway across the word to accept a &quot;no.&quot; <br>
<br>
::looks at the subject title::<br>
<br>
